column169: On June 17, 2024, one (1) 330-gallon tote of UN1814 was punctured while loading and released approximately fifteen (15) gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Hull's Environmental Services (HES) to remediate the impacted site.  Crews deployed granular absorbents to the impacted trailer and swept them in with hand tools. The damaged tote was transferred into a new 330-gallon tote. The empty, damaged tote was removed for disposal. All spent absorbents and cleanup debris were collected and containerized into three (3) 55-gallon drums for transport and disposal.  On June 20, 2024, R+L requested crews return to the site to address lingering odors inside the trailer and excess dried product that remained on interior and exterior surfaces of the trailer. CES dispatched a crew from Alpha-Omega Training and Compliance (AOTC) to assess and remediate. AOTC arrived and scraped excess material from the inside and outside trailer surfaces then wiped down surfaces with hot water and cleaning/neutralizing solution. All waste material was collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum and staged onsite for disposal.

On Thursday, June 27, 2024, a CN mechanical performing an inspection observed that the bottom outlet valve appeared to be leaking from tank car # UTLX 209759 along with a strong Ethanol type odor in the area. The employee notified the Waterloo Yard Master who in turn notified the CN Dangerous Goods Team. The tank car was set out to an isolation track (WA90) for inspection by a CN emergency response contractor. A CN emergency response contractor was dispatched to the location for mitigation. The contractor performed an inspection of the tank car and found the bottom outlet valve to be leaking from the threads of the bottom outlet valve cap. It was determined that there was a failure in the sealing surface of the valve seat to include a defective gasket. (The BOV cap was found to be less than tool tight and the BOV in the closed position and pinned upon initial inspection). CN emergency response contractor did observe cable seal to be correctly in place. The BOV cap was removed, and it was observed to be leaking past the closed ball. The BOV valve handle was cycled several times to the open and closed position to free any debris that may have been trapped in the BOV sealing surface potentially causing the leak. The BOV cap was then removed and observed for 20 minutes to ensure there was no further leakage from the valve. It was noted that the BOV cap gasket was deformed and was replaced. The bottom outlet valve cap was then re-installed and tightened with a 36" pipe wrench. Upon tightening the BOV cap, CN emergency response contractor proceeded to place new cable seals on the BOV / Cap.

Tanker was parked over gravel/dirt portion of private property at our facility in Rahway, NJ. Lading was Waste  Corrosive liquid, nos in a specification DOT-407 cargo tank constructed of stainles steel, which is an authorized  package and compatible with the lading. Driver parked loaded tanker in our yard and didn't ensure the internal valve  was fully closed before leaving. Blank flange cap on end of wet line had been recently replaced and mistakenly was  replaced with an aluminum cap. Lading was leaking slowly through ajar internal valve into wet line and corroded  aluminum blank flange cap from within. Corrosion to point of spillage and approx. 50 gallons of lading leaked onto  the ground. Product was cleaned up and site remediated by in-house labor and materials. Mechanical repairs to  trailer and subsequent testing underway as of this reporting.
column170: After incident review call with managers and affected employees, enhanced training and mentorship will be provided  to all staff responsible for preparation and transport of hazardous materials. This will include reinforcing importance  of lading compatability with packaging, and identifying difference between aluminum and steel components of  packaging. Driver in question has been counselled re: making sure all closures fully seated. If any other information  becomes available to update this report, an edited and updated report will be immediately filed.

column169: On June 11, 2024, four (4) 1-gallon pails of UN3264 were crushed in transit and released approximately 2.5-gallons of product to the trailer interior and pavement below. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Environmental Restoration (ER) to remediate the impacted site. ER discovered that R+L personnel had placed four damaged drums into one (1) 15-gallon drum. ER personnel utilized a neutralizing agent to remediate the trailer. Granular absorbents were then placed on the impacted areas and swept using hand tools. ER then broke down the impacted pallet completing remediation. All spent absorbents as well as the pallet were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum. Both drums were staged onsite for future disposal.

A fiberboard box with signs of release was discovered during sort operations at the MEMH location. The fiberboard box contained three glass bottles that were packaged in individual plastic sealed bags. One of the bottles broke and spilled it's contents inside of the fiberboard box. All contents were placed into a steel salvage package and anew declaration will be obtained for movement.
attachment Name:Hazmat- Damaged Haz Mat Package Disposition 04302024.pdf

The package was discovered wet upon opening the trailer at the beginning of the pre-load sort at around 2:30am according to the OPS Supervisors on duty.  Package was then placed into red line hazmat bin & brought to QA for inspection.  When the package was discovered by QA, the box was soaked/stained on one side & ripped open.  The fiberboard box also had several class 8 corrosive markings, UN/USA markings, & hazmat shipping paperwork attached to it.  4 bottles of Nu-Brite Condenser Coil Cleaner were found inside the box w/ 2 each separated by a fiberboard liner.  2 of the bottle's caps had been crushed/bent downward into the body & the 3rd was crushed/bent/squeezed on its body in the middle on each side, causing the contents to leak through the caps.  3 of the bottles were dented on several areas as well.  During the inspection process an additional red line hazmat bin was used to inspect the box & contents.  A long green rubber glove & several biodegradable single use nitrile gloves were used to handle the corrosive substance.  The Improper Shipping Form & Damaged Package Report were filled out & all of the Contents, fiberboard box, & PPE were placed into a lined salvage drum.

Clean Harbors was dispatched to the site. Upon the personnel observed that the released material impacted a 1ft-by-3ft area of the trailer wall and estimated that forty (40) cardboard packages containing 1-gallon each was damaged from a load shift and released approximately five (5) gallons of material.  Clean Harbors  personnel deployed a cleaner to the impacted area and used absorbent rags to recover the spent material. The impacted rags were containerized along with impacted cardboard into five (5) 55-gallon poly drums. The generated waste was staged onsite at the consignee’s location. A second response the next day at the terminal resulted in one (1) ounce of material leaking from the repalletized packages.  The contractor deployed a cleaner again to the impacted area of the trailer floor and used absorbent rags to recover the spent material. Clean Harbors generated two (2) additional 55-gallon poly drums. The two (2) drums of waste were staged onsite at the terminal in a secure location prior to the contractor demobilization.  The generated waste will remain onsite for the ESTES DGRM team to coordinate disposal.

column169: XPO Logistics terminal XHG experienced a UN1791 Dynachlor release from a 275-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 50-gallons of product released to a 10’ x 30’ area of the trailer floor and concrete lot below due to a puncture caused by dunnage. The material was transferred into a new tote for shipment on. Absorbents and citric acid were deployed to clean and neutralize the impacted areas. All impacted absorbents were collected into (3) 55-gallon poly drums. The damaged tote was then cut up and containerized into a 4th 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: On June 19, 2024, one (1) 5-gallon pail of printer ink was damaged in transit and released approximately two (2) gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Environmental Works, Inc. (EWI) to remediate the impacted site. EWI personnel deployed granular absorbents to the impacted trailer and swept them in with hand tools. All spent absorbents were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum and the damaged pail of UN1210 was containerized in one (1) 55-gallon drum for disposal.

column169: While unloading freight from trailer material handler discovered a drum that was slightly leaking from the bottom. Further investigation revealed that a binder clip that was holding the paperwork for the drum had wedged itself between the drum and the pallet the drum was staged on and during the course of transportation the drum shifted and hut the binder clip which consequently slightly punctured the drum contributing to the unintentional release. Spilled material was neutralized and cleaned with absorbent and placed into a recovery container as was the punctured drum.
column170: This was sort of an abnormity situation - maybe the paperwork should not be attached to the freight with a binder clip and instead placed into a packing list envelope to help prevent these types of unintentional releases from occurring.

column169: On 2024/06/10 a CN transportation & mechanical employees observed liquid coming from the top and running down the sides of tank car # UTLX 204748 at the CN Proctor Yard in Proctor, MN. While performing switching operations. The on shift CN Transportation supervisor made all internal notifications to activate an emergency response to investigate the cause and perform a cleanup.  A CN emergency response contractor was dispatched to the location and found tank car UTLX 204748 with (3) of the (6) manway cover swing bolts to be loose (could turn by hand), preventing a proper seal of the gasket allowing the contents to leak out when the car moved. Both the liquid and vapor line valve securement plugs were installed properly tool tight. The BOV cap was found tool tight. All the shipper security seals were found to be intact at the time of inspection.  The security seals were removed from the manway cover and the protective housing cover. The manway cover was opened to inspect the gasket which was found to be in good condition. The manway cover was closed, and all swing bolts were properly tightened. The valve securement plugs were inspected and found tool tight. As well the BOV cap was found secured tool tight and new security seals were applied to the manway as well as the combination housing. The exterior of the tank car was cleaned off utilizing a rags and absorbent pads. Once car was cleaned car was released back to transportation to continue to destination

The spent material was gathered and containerized into two (2) 55-gallon poly drums and the damaged plastic jugs were placed into one (1) 55-gallon poly drum. column169: At approximately 06:09 AM on 06/24/24 I recieved notification that the tank car had sloshed product (Substituted Phenol) from under the manway. The car was located in track 47 at our North Yard, the shipper was contacted and they elected to use our Haz-Mat Contractor M&M Protection LLC to respond.  Upon arrival it was noted that all 8 swing bolts were less than tool tight and the gasket was worn. These issues were corrected by M&M, new gasket, swing bolts tighten in a star pattern with no more evidence of product leaking. The car was washed and all spillage/residue was remediated.

Checking the transfer line, the associate noticed Van 53022 (FCI) was leaking onto the gravel. The associate notified the foreman and pulled the van onto the concrete roadway to get it off the gravel. We assessed the area and then we took the van to the CSF to be offloaded to find the leaking container. About halfway in the trailer we found the drum with a dime size hole in it and the contents had all leaked onto the trailer floor except for approx. 15 gal. We finished unloading the van and we processed the load. We cleaned the trailer floor with floor dry. We also cleaned the TL and the drive. The material that leaked onto the drive stained the concrete. The Transfer Line spill on the gravel was approx. 1 gal. it was contained in a 3 foot radius pot hole so we added floor dry to absorb the material.  We took a before and after sample to the lab with the cin. (519142) we used on the drum that leaked. All effected areas have been cleaned. We generated 1 (1/4 Full) Tote. Tote is labeled with a Haz. Label with the info. needed and placed in the on hold area.

R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from HazChem Environmental (HCE) to remediate the impacted site. column169: On 6/17/2024, the BNSF San Bernardino hub personnel reported Unit JBHU 262270 (Waybill Hazardous) as leaking a substance from the rear of the container that did reach the ground after unit was de   ramped from a train. Unit was taken to the Hazmat Pit for safety. On the behalf of the shipper, approved contractor United Pumping was contacted and dispatched to complete inspection.  Interior inspection revealed 15 supersacks in 2 rows throughout the container. Source of the leak was determined to be one supersack filled with pool chlorine granules in the rear of the unit. The cause for the Leak was determined to be less than a pound of pool chlorine leaked from the top of the supersack, contributing to the material leak. The granules mixed with the condensation in the unit creating a liquid which leaked from the rear of the container. Total quantity of leaked liquid was approximately 16 ounces of product. During the inspection a bullboard was located at the rear of the load as securement.  Contractor United Pumping completed remediation of the unit and all affected areas. Spilled product was cleaned and disposed of.

Loaded trailer was on our yard in Beaumont, TX when it was discovered to be Ieaking from a flange. The emergency shut off was used in hopes of stopping the leak. This attempt did not work because the product was actually coming from the flange above the external valve. Proper PPE was donned and the pressure was released from the top of the trailer. This slowed the leak down enough for our shop supervisor to don the proper PPE and check all the bolts and nuts on the flange. We found two nuts were very loose. These nuts were tightened up and the leak was completely stop. After our immediate investigation was completed, we discover that the two nuts that were lose had two lock washers that had flattened out not allowing the nuts to stay tight.
column170: valve is removed then new lock washers must be used on every bolt. As part of our PM system we added that all nuts and bolts must be checked to ensure the nuts are staying tight. If lose nuts are discovered during the PM, then new lock washer will be put in place of the old lock washers. ,

column169: On June 19, 2024, one (1) 330-gallon tote of UN3265 was punctured by fallen freight and released approximately three (3) gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Ancon Services (AS) to remediate the impacted site. AS personnel utilized hand tools, neutralizers, granular absorbents and absorbent pads to the UN3265-impacted trailer floor, wooden slab, tote exterior and swept them up. AS deconstructed the wooden slab and conducted a gravity tote transfer into a new 330-gallon poly tote. All spent absorbents were collected and containerized into one (1) 30-gallon drum. The original tote was deconstructed with and collected into one (1) 55-gallon poly drum.

The crew overpacked the damaged drum in one (1) 95-gallon OP. The crew utilized absorbents and hand tools to remediate the site and containerized all impacted material in two (2) 55-gallon drums for disposal.   On June 18, 2024, FCE returned to continue remediation. Crews removed the impacted wooden pallets and packaging materials. All impacted debris was containerized as waste in two (2) 55-gallon drums and staged onsite for disposal.  On June 20, 2024, FCE returned to the site to further over pack the affected cargo of four (4) 55-gallon fiber drums. Crews collected and containerized the four (4) fiber drums into four (4) 95-gallon over pack poly drums and staged them onsite for disposal.

column169: Forklift strike

A Veolia employee was offloading a pallet from a trailer at Veolia's 10 day intransit facility in Menomonee Falls, WI when they noticed a spill of material upon moving a pallet. The bags on the pallet were poorly shrink wrapped, allowing for the material to shift due to vibrations while in transit resulting in tears to the bags. One bag released contents estimated to be in a quantity of approximately 10 lbs of hazardous waste. No injuries or chemical exposures were reported. The bags were overpacked for continued transportation to the disposal facility.
column170: Veolia employees who picked up the load from the shipper have been reminded to make sure all hazardous material/waste of properly packed in authorized packaging and loaded securely prior to being placed in transit.

column169: A Veolia employee was moving drums into a trailer utilizing a drum grabber/clamp at Veolia's ten day intransit facility in Fremont, CA. The drum grabber/clamp gets a hold on the drum from the top and bottom portion of the drum lip.  When picking up the next row of 55 gal metal drums, the employee tilted the mast back. Before driving forward, the employee noticed a liquid stream coming down on the side of one of the drums. Approximately 8 oz of the chemical was spilled and landed on the warehouse concrete floor. The spill did not enter any drains and was immediately cleaned up. The leaking drum was placed into a salvage container. There was no evidence of punctures or deficiencies to the drum itself.
column170: An evaluation to the drum grabber/ clamp is in progress to determine if they are in need of replacement. Additionally, a refresher training will be performed with the employee regarding properly inspecting equipment before performing a task. Employees will be also be reminded on how to properly manage drums/containers when utilizing a drum grabber/clamp.

column43: LITHIUM ION BATTERIES CONTAINED IN EQUIPMENT INCLUDING LITHIUM ION POLYMER BATTERIES
column169: AT THE UPS MIAMI FLORIDA FACILITY, NINE SKIDS MOVING TO COLOMBIA VIA UPS AIR CARGO SERVICE WERE FOUND CONTAINING BOXES WITH COVERED LITHIUM BATTERY MARKS. ALL NINE SKIDS ARE BLACK SHRINK WRAPPED WITHOUT ANY DANGEROUS GOODS INDICATORS ON THE OUTER COVERING. A TOTAL OF 23 BOXES EACH CONTAINING 72 WIRELESS LITHIUM-ION BATTERY POWERED MYJOY COOL EARBUDS WERE FOUND. DURING FORKLIFT MOVEMENT OF THE SKIDS, WE CAN SEE LITHIUM BATTERY MARKS UNDERNEATH ON THE VERY BOTTOM OF THE FREIGHT. THE AIR WAYBILL DOES NOT INDICATE LITHIUM BATTERIES ARE BEING SHIPPED TO COLOMBIA. THERE ARE NO DANGEROUS GOODS MARKS OR LABELS ON ANY PART OF THE OUTER BLACK SHRINK WRAPPED FREIGHT. EHMA EXPRESS INC, 8509 NW 68TH ST, MIAMI FL 33166 IS THE ISSUING CARRIER'S AGENCY ON THE AIR WAYBILL. SHIPPER'S NAME AND ADDRESS IS SUNRISE FINANCIAL BUSINESS, S.A. C/O FIFO WIRELESS, INC, 10900 NW 21ST STREET SUITE 210, MIAMI FL 33172.

column59: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column169: 3rd party carrier began loading storage tanks and the middle tank that was OOS was over-pressurized resulting in a vapor release. The liquid valve was turned off and locked, but the vapor valve was not, allowing vapor pressure to be put in the tank. The local FD was called and responded to the PRVs "popping" but they had already re-seated by the time they arrived. Approx. time of release was 5 min.
column170: The vapor valve that was opened by the carrier has now been turned off and locked and tagged out.  The out of service tank was evacuated of all remaining propane and has been confirmed empty and is being prepped for repair.

column169: On June 4, 2024, one (1) 55-gallon drum of acetone was damaged and released approximately one-half (0.5) gallon of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental (FCE) to remediate the impacted site. FCE personnel deployed granular absorbents to the acetone-impacted trailer and swept them in with hand tools. All spent absorbents were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum. The damaged drum of product was placed into one (1) 85-gallon overpack. All drums were staged onsite for future disposal.

column169: According to the information obtained, the following occurred. While unloading, one 2,450Ib tote was discovered leaking. Area was isolated and contractor was dispatched. GrayMar Environmental responded to perform the cleanup. Upon arrival on site, GrayMar Environmental inspected the leaking tote and determined the cap was faulty, which resulted in the release of approximately 0.5 gallon of product. Free product released to trailer floor and dock at customer location. GrayMar Environmental used absorbent material and rags to wipe the area clean, and transferred the leaking tote into a recovery tote to be sent on to the consignee. One 55-gallon drum of spent absorbent and cleanup debris was generated during the cleanup. Product was contained to an impervious surface and did not impact soil or threaten to impact state waters. There were no injuries or exposures reported.

A Contractor estimated that 2-gallons of corrosive liquid released onto adjacent product, packaging including cardboard and shrink wrap/bubble-wrap, and the wooden trailer floor in a 8’x4’ area. Citric Acid was applied as a neutralizer and oil dry was laid down to absorb the release. Two drums of waste were generated for disposal. No storm-drains, waterways, or soil were affected by this incident.

column169: At approximately 18:25hrs 6/20/2024, Southeastern Freight Lines employee reversed a forklift out of trailer onto the loading dock and turned around when he pulled forward, he accidently punctured a 275-gallon tote IBC containing UN3264 product with the forks of the forklift this put a one-foot gash on the bottom comer of the tote. Causing approximately 200 gallons of product to be released on the loading dock, apron and parking lot. The forklift operator and out bound operations manager applied floor dry attempting to contain the product. The tote was maneuvered on its side in efforts to stop the spillage. None of the chemicals were near or entered any type of drain system. Southeastern Freight Lines Safety was notified approximately at 18:45hrs. Hazmat one was notified approximately at 18:54hrs. Hazmat contracted Oil Mop to the spillage Oil Mop arrived at the premises at approximately 20:36hrs. and advised most of the product has already dried up so they are going to start getting neutralizer down on it, put absorbent, and recoup it into poly drums. There is about 60-70g left in the old tote that they are going to transfer into a new tote and will dispose of the old one. 20:36hrs Hazmat one notified the Texas Spill Reporting Hotline at 800-832-8224 and spoke with Anthony he will notify region 10 the Report#20242263. 06/21/2024 15:20hrs Mop Oil called and said that they have finished cleaning the parking lot. They have moved inside and have sodium bicarb down on the floor. They will get all of this swept up and then must finish transferring the remaining product out of the tote. They are taking 4-drums with them for disposal and will have to return to get the tote of product later.

column169: On 2024/06/10 a CN transportation & mechanical employees observed liquid coming from the top and running down the sides of tank car # UTLX 212116 at the CN Proctor Yard in Proctor, MN. While performing switching operations. The on shift CN Transportation supervisor made all internal notifications to activate an emergency response to investigate the cause and perform a cleanup.  A CN emergency response contractor was dispatched to the location and found the manway swing bolts were or appeared to be over tightened and compromised the lid gasket, pinching it and preventing a proper seal of the gasket allowing the contents to leak out when the car moved. Both the liquid and vapor line valve securement plugs were installed properly tool tight. The BOV cap was found tool tight. All the shipper security seals were found to be intact at the time of inspection.  The security seals were removed from the manway cover and the protective housing cover on UTLX 212116. The manway lid was opened to inspect the lid gasket which was found to be pinched/crushed. The damaged manway lid gasket was removed and replaced with a compatible lid gasket, then the manway cover was closed, and all swing bolts were properly tightened. The valve securement plugs were inspected and found tool tight. As well the BOV cap was found secured tool tight and new security seals were applied to the manway as well as the combination housing. The exterior of the tank car was cleaned off utilizing a rags and absorbent pads. Once car was cleaned car was released back to transportation to continue to destination.

The released product, damaged drum, and oil-dri was placed into an 85-gallon poly drum and 55-gallon poly drum and staged in OS&D. There were no drains, soils or waterways reported to have been impacted by the release.

column169: Unsecured freight

On 6/3/24, at 1232 hours, personnel in the NCVA Railroad Boykins, VA Yard discovered GBRX709256, a loaded tank car of Sodium Hydroxide Solution, had leaked from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Chemserve Terminals, was notified via CHEMTREC 2024060300092. Hepaco, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene as well as a representative from Chemserve Terminals and found the air line valve open and secondary closure plug not installed. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative- Matt Law 757-544-0784. Contractor personnel closed the valve and reinstalled the plug and decontaminated the car. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport.

XPO- XDE contacted ERTS regarding a leaking 250-gallon metal tote containing hazardous product, Zinc  Octoate 8%. A Contractor discovered that the lid to the tote was loose and likely the cause of the release. It was estimated that 5-gallons of product spilled from the lid impacting the metal tote itself, the wooden trailer  floor, and the steel grate on trailer floor. The total impact are was estimated to be 6’x6’. The Contractor was  able to tighten the lid and perform a slosh test confirming that adjustments made to the lid were successful and  the tote is in proper working order to ship on to the Consignee. One 55-gallon DM was generated for waste  disposal containing impacted cardboard, PPE, and absorbent pads/rags. No storm-drains, waterways, or soil  were involved in this incident

On 6/26/2024, at 1048 hours, personnel in the CSXT Ashtabula Yard discovered TILX 113642, a residue tank car of Hydrochloric Acid, leaking from the protective housing area. The car was isolated and the shipper, INEOS, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2024-0626-143). EnviroServe, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the primary liquid line closure flange not properly prepared for transportation. Contractor personnel properly secured the closure and decontaminated the car. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative- Jeanne Kochevar (440-228-8373).

Hepaco responded and observed approximately 10-pounds of Cryolite released from the damaged plastic gaylord. The release impacted a 10’X23’ area on the trailer floor. No drains or soil were impacted. Hepaco recovered the Cryolite. Hepaco unloaded the trailer, used simple green rags, wiped down the trailer, freighted, and reloaded the trailer. Hepaco created one 5-gallon poly drum of waste. Hepaco left the waste on-site with the XPO dock manager.

column169: On June 25, 2024, four (4) 5-gallon pails of paint were crushed in transit and released approximately three (3) gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from GrayMar Environmental Services (GMES) to remediate the impacted site. GMES personnel deployed granular absorbents to the paint-impacted trailer and swept them in with hand tools. All spent absorbents, debris, and damaged pails were collected and containerized into three (3) 55-gallon drums to be staged onsite for future disposal.

column169: It was reported that approximately 2-gallons of Sodium Hydroxide Solution (UN1824) was released. The caller stated that the released product was contained to the dock floor at door #17. ERTS advised contractor HEPACO would respond due to the corrosive state of the product and amount released. HEPACO advised Oil Dri was applied to the impacted area and the concrete dock was neutralized with a muriatic acid solution. The damaged drum was then placed into a 95-gallon poly drum and the impacted absorbents, pads and PPE were placed into a 55-gallon poly drum for disposal. There were no drains, soils or waterways reported to have been impacted by the release.

column169: HAZMAT RESPONDER DISCOVERED DAMAGED AND LEAKING CARTON ON PALLET OUTSIDE DMP AREA, INSIDE TOTE. column169: A Veolia employee was operating a forklift with a drum grabber attachment to load drums into a trailer. During this process, the employee observed an odor. The employee stopped operating the forklift and went to investigate the source of the odor. Further investigation revealed that a drum in the trailer was leaking from a small pin sized puncture in the middle of its body.  Approximately one pint of the liquid chemical had leaked from the drum and released onto the trailer floor. The duration of the spill was less than 5 minutes. The employee removed the leaking drum from the trailer and placed it into a salvage drum with absorbent. The spill was cleaned up by two other Veolia employees that were on the premises.
column170: After a thorough review of the incident, Veolia believes that the drum got damaged due to the forklift operator going too fast and while driving over the dock plate. The bumps from the uneven surface caused the drum to pivot and the drum to hit the support on the drum grabber. In addition, the employee failed to tilt the load back on the forklift to prevent the drums from rocking. Veolia has prohibited the employee from any further forklift operation until he has been trained and re-evaluated for safe operations. Lastly, a reminder training was provided to other employees at the Veolia, Fremont location to make sure they keep the loads low and tilted back along with monitoring their speed especially when going over transitions (uneven surfaces) which may cause the drums rock. The drum grabber has also been evaluated to check for any damage or failure in the equipment.

On 06-23-2024 a CN Mechanical employee detected a strong foul odor emanating from tank car # GLNX 23299 containing UN 1993/Crude Sulfate Turpentine/Class 3/PG II while performing work on the repair track at the CN Mays Yard in Harahan, LA. The employee notified his supervisor who in turn made notification to the CN Dangerous Goods Team that initiated a response. The on-duty CN Dangerous Goods Officer dispatched an emergency response contractor to the location to investigate. The responding contractor noted a strong odor upon arrival to the rail car's location. There were no visible liquid leaks observed. The inspection of the top fittings revealed the manway cover gasket protruding from the manway cover. A 4-gas meter with a PID sensor detected 16 PPM of VOC's at the sealing surface of the manway cover. The shipper security seal was found to be intact upon arrival. The manway cover security seal was removed, and the cover opened for the purpose of inspecting the gasket. The inspection revealed the gasket to be torn preventing a proper seal allowing the product vapors to escape. The gasket was replaced followed by the re-securement of the swing bolts. The area was tested again with the gas meter which was non-detect for VOC's. A replacement security seal was applied to the manway cover. The liquid and air valves within the protective housing were also inspected for proper securement prior to deeming the rail car safe for continued transportation. The rail car was released back to the transportation department for continued transportation to destination.

On June 19, 2024, at 8AM, an OxyChem driver arrived at Air Liquide in Lubbock, TX, to deliver Hydrochloric Acid. The driver checked in with security, then positioned the tractor and trailer at the unloading sight and met with the customer representative to sign the BOL, as well as OxyChem's "In the Interest of Safety" form. At approximately 8:10 AM, the unloading hose was connected to the customers flange, the trailer internal product valve was opened, and the air inlet valve to the trailer was opened. As the driver was opening the external valve, Hydrochloric Acid began to leak around the threaded connection of a CPVC ball valve that is part of the trailer blow down piping system. The driver proceeded to the front of the trailer where he closed the air inlet valve, and then around the truck to the left front trailer fender where he activated the emergency shutoff valve. He then contacted the customer representative to make them aware of the leak. Approximately 10 gallons of product leaked into a containment area. No injuries, chemical exposure or environmental impact resulted from this leak.
column170: The area was washed down with water and the driver was able to inspect the valve. The driver found the thread coupling to the ball valve was not tight which allowed product to escape. He reconnected the coupling, pressurized the line with air and checked for leaks with soapy water, then unloaded the trailer without any problems.  Continue to check this style of valve when the trailer is re-torqued after its third delivery following its DOT cargo tank inspection.  Communicate the issue to OxyChem mechanics to increase awareness when installing these types of valves.  Have OxyChem mechanics check these types of valves during routine preventive maintenance checks to ensure they are tight.

It was reported that an unknown quantity of Delta-Therm AE 7102 Isocyanate was released from (1) 3400-pound steel tank due to improper loading (the strap was not placed correctly and caused the valve to open). The release impacted the inside of the trailer. The tank was not damaged and they were able to get the valve closed and stopped releasing. No waste will be generated. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller and determined that terminal personnel are capable of cleaning the release with PPE available on site.

It was reported that 2-gallons of UN2289 Baxxodur® EC 201 released from a 2000-pound plastic tote due to improper loading. Clean Harbors was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 6ft-by-6ft area of the dock floor and estimated that two (2) gallons of material were released from one (1) 275-gallon tote. Clean Harbors personnel deployed absorbents and then swept up the released material. The damaged tote and recovered material were placed into four (4) 55-gallon poly drums and was staged onsite at the terminal prior to the contractor demobilization.

column169: On June 19, 2024, one (1) 55-gallon drum of sodium hydroxide was damaged in transit and released approximately one (1) gallon of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Indiana Spill Response (ISR) to remediate the impacted site. ISR personnel deployed granular absorbents and a neutralizing agent to remediate the site. All spent absorbents and debris were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum. The damaged containers of product were placed into one (1) 85-gallon drum for disposal.

column169: Car was found to be leaking during movement and was set out to the Rip track.  Upon inspection it was determined that the rupture disc was blown, and the cover/cap was missing.  The cable connecting the cover/cap to the trivent assembly was frayed.  The disc gave evidence of a surge that ruptured the disc in an outward direction.  I was unable to determine if a surge protector was present.  The disc was replaced, and the shipper was advised to get an MRU to replace the cover/cap and have the car requalified.

column169: XPO Logistics terminal USU experienced a UN3266 Offense release from (2) 5-gallon poly pails. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 10-gallons of product released to a 20’ x 6’ area of the trailer floor and a 3’ x 20’ area of the concrete lot below. The pallet tipped over in transit due to improper loading. The damaged pails were placed into a 55-gallon poly drum. The impacted area was cleaned with absorbents and citric acid to neutralize the release. All impacted absorbents and impacted pallets were placed into (8) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

It was reported that approximately 100-gallons of Sulfuric acid released from one (1) 275-gallon tote onto the trailer floor and asphalt underneath the trailer. The Tote was punctured on the bottom by a forklift during unloading, releasing to the trailer interior and onto the dock and parking lot. ERTS dispatched Hepaco to the site to assist with clean up. The contractor arrived on-site and confirmed the product affected a 20’x4’ area on the trailer floor and underneath the trailer floor. The contractor collected and containerized the Dilute Sulfuric Acid (35%) and all clean-up debris into six (6) 55-gallon drums and one (1) 275-gallon tote. All waste was stored onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

Driver stopped at rest area to take a break and to check on his load. When the driver walked around he noticed a drip coming from his trailer onto the drive tire he then though down some absorbent. The driver than called our emergency response line and a team was dispatched out at approximately 0845. The crew arrived at 1100 to investigate they found 3 drums that the lids were not secured tightly. The then unloaded the trailer to gain access to the containers wiping up any residue on the floor as they went. The 3 drums lids and rings were then tightened securely. The absorbents used to clean up the residue were then disposed of properly. The crew was done at 1700.

On Tuesday, 6/04/2024, at 1121 hours, an FRA Hazmat Inspector in the CSXT Queens Gate Yard discovered UTLX676824, a loaded tank car of Ammonium Nitrate, liquid, had leaked from the Vacuum Relief Valve (VRV). The car was isolated and the shipper, CF Industries Sales LLC, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report#2024-0604-00147). CSXT Hazmat personnel responded to the yard and observed dried product within the service equipment housing that had leaked from the VRV. The valve was not actively leaking at the time of response. The issue was identified as a defective Vacuum Relief Valve and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative, Roy Mathew, 224-804-7190, rmathew@cfindustries.com. The car was held out of transportation pending repair or replacement of the defective valve by a certified mobile repair unit.

column43: LITHIUM ION BATTERIES INCLUDING LITHIUM ION POLYMER BATTERIES
column169: DURING NORMAL HANDLING PROCESS AT THE UPS HONG KONG INTERNATIONAL CHEK LAP KOK FACILITY ONE AIR PACKAGE FROM HONG KONG DESTINED TO THE USA WAS OBSERVED SMOKING ON THE BELT. THE PACKAGE WAS IMMEDIATELY TAKEN AWAY FROM THE BELT AND PLACED IN A SEGREGATED AREA. THE SMOLDERING INCREASED AND SUBSEQUENTLY THE PACKAGE BEGAN BURNING. UPS STAFF USED A FIRE EXTINGUISHER TO EXTINGUISH THE FIRE. THE EVENT WAS DISCOVERED PRIOR TO THE PACKAGE BEING LOADED INTO AN AIR CONTAINER. THE PACKAGE HAD PASSED A DANGEROUS GOODS ACCEPTANCE AUDIT PRIOR TO THE LITHIUM BATTERY INCIDENT. THE PACKAGE WAS FULLY DECLARED WITH AN APPROPRIATE IATA SHIPPERS DECLARATION AS UN3480 LITHIUM ION BATTERIES, SECTION IA OF PACKING INSTRUCTION 965. AFTER THE EVENT WAS EXTINGUISHED, THE OPERATIONS NOTED THE INNER THREE BATTERIES WERE NOT PROPERLY SEPARATED OR PROTECTED. ADDITIONALLY, NO WATT HOUR MARKINGS WERE FOUND ON THE BATTERIES.  PER 49CFR 171.15, THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS CONTACTED BY TELEPHONE TO REPORT THE INCIDENT. THE OFFICER WAS UNABLE TO ACCEPT THE TELEPHONE REPORT DUE TO THE EVENT NOT OCCURRING IN THE USA.

column163: ASSISTANT MANAGER OF COMPLIANCE AND SAFETY
column169: Our tanker vehicle loaded full with 87 Gasoline was struck by another vehicle. Our trailer required to be towed. Before it was towed the damaged trailer was emptied by a third party company with a pumping truck, into an empty secondary tanker we had brought onto location. In the events of the pumping truck transferring the product, the pumping company did not verify that all of the product was transferred from one tank of the damaged truck to the corresponding tank of the new truck. In doing so, our 1100 gallon tank was overfilled and 20 gallons of gasoline was pushed out of the vapor recovery line on our trailer. The third party company used absorbent mats, brooms, absorbent socks, and clean up powder to mitigate the effects of the release.
column170: Training for the third party is recommended to confirm that the pumping truck is fully emptied before starting another transfer of product from one tank to the other. Sensors and another verification technique can also confirmed that the pumping truck either has product still or is empty before continuing the process.

column169: A leaking container of hydrogen peroxide and peroxyacetic acid was discovered at the Menomonee Falls 10-Day Dock while unloading a trailer at the 10 day intransit facility in Menomonee Falls, WI. The cardboard container was saturated with the liquid, and needed to be repackaged, as well as handled appropriately by a reactives trained Menomonee Falls Field Service employee. An investigation revealed the source of the spill was due to the closure not being secured on the inner package allowing for material to leak out of the top.
column170: Veolia dock employees have been reminded to verify container integrity, and report container defects as observed. Shippers should ensure the closures on all inner packaging(s) are securely closed and in good condition prior to offering the package for transportation.

column169: Package is an RTS from station 814. The exterior packaging had no orientation arrows, and no limited quantity diamond label on the FedEx repack box. The box is wet and hardened on the underside. Inside, a lot of paper filling materials were used. A clear plastic hazmat waste bag was used to contain the inner box that the shipment originally came with. The bag was secured haphazardly with a bunch of tape. The original outer box is wet all over and a diamond cut mark can be seen. The place where the limited quantity label used to be. This can be verified from the spidr image of the original package when it was picked up. Reviewing the DPR of the package, the package was not flagged as a dangerous goods, when in fact, 3 items of 2 different limited quantity was found. The original contents were 2 qty of 1 gallon metal container of Clear Guard EF, 1 metal can of Solvent Thinner, 1 qty 8 oz plastic container of Copper C Metal Coating, 1 qty of 8 oz Gold C Metal Coating, and 20fl oz high volume low pressure gravity feed spray gun. All items are products of Sculpt Nouveau. 1 container of Clear Guard EF was dented and the plastic seal for the lid came off and spill 3/4 of its contents. The Solvent Thinner was also dented and spilled from the cap around half of its content. The other gallon of Clear Guard EF was wet but salvageable, so are the metal coating, the content of the spray gun can be salvaged but the packaging is ruined. The package did not get a DG Nav Dangerous Goods Report when it was initially discovered but instead removed the Limited quantity diamond label and flagged the package non-hazardous and then RTS the package completely, including the damaged LQ.

column43: COATING SOLUTION ( INCLUDES SURFACE TREATMENTS OR COATINGS USED FOR INDUSTRIAL OR OTHER PURPOSES SUCH AS VEHICLE UNDERCOATING, DRUM OR BARREL LINING )
column169: Hazmat UN1139 was unloaded in the small unload and van scanned to WA 271 at 6:21AM. The package wasn't noticed to be wet or leaking until the driver inspected the package on his vehicle. Upon the driver's coding, Quality Assurance was immediately notified of the wet package placed in plastic bags to contain the spill. Upon external inspection, The package was wet, had a strong odor, and labels were faded from the liquid. After the tracking number was identified, the internal inspection began. 1 gallon of coval ultimate top coat gloss was leaking due from pressure on the cap and 1 quart of the flammable liquid coating solution leaked out. 3 quarts still remain intact in the 1 gallon plastic bottle. The fiberboard box, plastic bottle containing the coating solution, and the plastic bags were placed securely in a hazardous materials bag and then inside a salvage drum. There was no inner packing materials to lessen the pressure on the cap of the coating solution to prevent the lid from loosening.
column170: It is my recommendation that a cardboard liner be used at the base of the cap when transporting this specific hazmat product to prevent spills in the future.

column169: Package is an RTS from station 814. The exterior packaging had no orientation arrows, and no limited quantity diamond label on the FedEx repack box. The box is wet and hardened on the underside. Inside, a lot of paper filling materials were used. A clear plastic hazmat waste bag was used to contain the inner box that the shipment originally came with. The bag was secured haphazardly with a bunch of tape. The original outer box is wet all over and a diamond cut mark can be seen. The place where the limited quantity label used to be. This can be verified from the spidr image of the original package when it was picked up. Reviewing the DPR of the package, the package was not flagged as a dangerous goods, when in fact, 3 items of 2 different limited quantity was found. The original contents were 2 qty of 1 gallon metal container of Clear Guard EF, 1 metal can of Solvent Thinner, 1 qty 8 oz plastic container of Copper C Metal Coating, 1 qty of 8 oz Gold C Metal Coating, and 20fl oz high volume low pressure gravity feed spray gun. All items are products of Sculpt Nouveau. 1 container of Clear Guard EF was dented and the plastic seal for the lid came off and spill 3/4 of its contents. The Solvent Thinner was also dented and spilled from the cap around half of its content. The other gallon of Clear Guard EF was wet but salvageable, so are the metal coating, the content of the spray gun can be salvaged but the packaging is ruined. The package did not get a DG Nav Dangerous Goods Report when it was initially discovered but instead removed the Limited quantity diamond label and flagged the package non-hazardous and then RTS the package completely, including the damaged LQ.

column169: On June 02, 2024 at 1430 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar personnel in Laredo, Texas regarding the release of approximately 7 gallons of WHT03P1 Monomer-Free Polyester Pigment Dispersion. Contractors were dispatched to the site to perform all onsite clean-up activities. Upon arrival, contractors confirmed the release of a total of 7 gallons of WHT03P1 Monomer-Free Polyester Pigment Dispersion (UN1866, 3 III) from (3) 5-gallon plastic pails. The release was caused by the pallet not having any dunnage, and the pails falling during transit. The release was contained to an area on the trailer floor and a 4ft x 4ft area of concrete beneath the trailer. Contractors were able to clean the release with absorbents and the proper PPE. The damaged pails containing material for reprocessing, were placed in (1) 55-gallon DF and the waste was placed in (1) 55-gallon DF and taken offsite by contractors for proper disposal.

While attempting to receive material from our vendor, our receiving personnel identified what they believed could be hazardous material but the packaging only had a limited quantity marking and no safety data sheets. After acquiring the SDS from the vendor, the material was confirmed to be hazardous.
column170: The material was labeled as limited quantity, when it should have been labeled with Class 3 Flammable liquid labels. The SDS should have been with the material, and an emergency contact number should have been provided in case there was a leak or spill. The proper shipping name and UN number should have been present on the package so the material could be safely and properly identified and handled.

The spill was cleaned up with oil dry and the drum was overpacked for continued transportation to the disposal facility.

Pkg Info ( TRK NBR=275942772492 PKG TYPE=Package (box/drum/jerrican/composite) PHY STATE=Liquid TRANSPORTATION PHASE=Unloading ) Commodity Info ( UNDG NBR=3480 CLASS=90 PSN TEXT=Lithium Ion Batteries PKG GRP=N/A SPILLED QTY=0 CONTAINER CAPACITY=500 CONTAINER UOM=Liquid - Milliliter MATERIAL CONSTRUCTION=D - Fiberboard or cardboard NUMBER IN SHIPMENT=1 NUMBER FAILED=0 INNER PKG TYPE=3 - Box TOTAL AMT IN EACH CONTAINER=2 TOTAL UOM=Solid - Kilogram TECH NAME=Section IB )On 6/16/2024 at approximately 1950, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 906768 at the ramp facility in Denver, reporting and undeclared dangeorus goods spill.  The shipment consisted of three glass bottles of hydrochloric acid and lithium battery powerbank. Two of the bottles spilled in transit, one of the bottles appeared to have shattered and the other leaked.
